| PUBLIC LIVES 
PUBLIC LIVES; Charm at the Top: It Only Looks Easy, Folks

By JAN HOFFMANJUNE 2, 1999



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









Correction AppendedTHERE is certainly ample reason to harbor unkind thoughts -- O.K., full-blown resentment -- toward Candace Krugman Beinecke.As Ms. Beinecke, she is a highly regarded corporate lawyer with blue-chip clients like Viacom, the entertainment giant, and PricewaterhouseCoopers, the accounting megalosaur. As Mrs. Beinecke, she has married into a family of great wealth and position, who give to the arts, the environment, Andover and Yale.It gets worse.She is naturally thin and never exercises.She doesn't need a lot of sleep.She doesn't look her age (52).She remembers to send thank-you notes -- her penmanship is clean and elegant -- and has taught her two sons the importance of doing so.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Do we hate her yet? No? Wait. Here's the killer:Her own relatives and in-laws love one another so much that they vacation together, even when she's not on the trip! Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





But in person, Ms. Beinecke is difficult to growl at, for she turns out to be possessed of a low-key charm and approachable warmth. Those qualities, as well as her prodigious work habits, helped insure that the recent vote by the executive committee of Hughes Hubbard & Reed to name her its new ''chair'' (the firm's term) was unanimous. Ambitious female lawyers, take heart: while Ms. Beinecke is the first woman, no kidding, to lead a major New York law firm, she got there by being good at what she does and, apparently, by not creating a welter of competitive jealousy among the male and female partners she surpassed.Ms. Beinecke advises female lawyers in particular to develop their own style and not mimic role models. ''Don't wear someone else's clothes if they don't fit,'' she said. ''I tried on several when I was starting out. I looked at big, brash, bullying types and tried yelling and screaming.'' She rolled her eyes. (She is soft spoken.)''I had a brief phase of wearing corporate-looking suits. I even tried wearing very short skirts. I had no idea what I was doing.''Eventually she settled on an untraditional look. Yesterday, in her office overlooking New York Harbor, she was wearing navy gabardine pants, heels with ankle straps, a glass necklace and matching earrings of surprisingly vivid hues, and an apple-green blazer. There was nothing corporate-looking about this quintessentially corporate lawyer.AND she has occasionally taken an untraditional approach in negotiating rooms, relying on gentle charm to defuse tension. During a volatile session involving a half-billion-dollar acquisition, Ms. Beinecke's client, the buyer, insisted that the seller agree to ongoing liability insurance. The angry seller packed up his papers, saying, ''I can't let my kids be part of this!''
Newsletter Sign Up
Continue reading the main story

  


