Determined to rescue the deal, Ms. Beinecke replied, with a light laugh, ''Oh, please let me be one of those children!'' Her client turned ashen. But the seller chortled and sat back down at the table.Clients say her charm is a cloak for a tenacious, imaginative negotiator. Even when she has bested her opponents, she leaves a residue of good will. In 1987, when Sumner M. Redstone made a competitive and ultimately successful bid to take over her client, Viacom, ''She was tough, fair and she listened,'' said Philippe Dauman, Viacom's deputy chairman and executive vice president. The new team swept out most of the old team, but kept her and her firm.Ms. Beinecke, who has been with the 300-lawyer firm since graduating from Rutgers Law School, said that as a baby lawyer she assumed she would become a litigator, fighting for clients in court. But she discovered that she preferred corporate practice, giving legal and financial advice to clients on reorganization, divestiture, acquisition.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

''Clients came to know me and appreciate that I would kill myself for them,'' she said genially.In 1970, when she entered the job market, women were asked by prospective employers whether they could handle the demanding hours of a corporate practice as well as family responsibilities. These days, the question is not raised, but the issue remains. Although Hughes Hubbard is known as a good place for women to practice -- it has flex-time arrangements and a fifth of its partners are women -- Ms. Beinecke did come up the hard way, working endless hours and taking a first maternity leave of only two months.''There were many nights when I wasn't home and I would have loved more time with my kids,'' she said. ''But you teach by example. My sons understand that it's exciting to be engaged and involved in work. And they learned how to have dinner at 9 P.M.''She grew up in Paterson, N.J., where her father practiced law and her mother, who was known professionally in the 1940's as Tippie Taylor, a radio host (but privately as Sylvia Altschuler), encouraged her to be a lawyer.In terms of credibility, Ms. Beinecke's biggest obstacle, perhaps, has not been her sex, but her status as Mrs. Beinecke, the wife of Frederick Beinecke, a scion of a great family.  (Yes, as in that Yale library.) There are boards that need attending to, benefits to grace, households to run.''People say to me, 'Why do you do this?' '' she said.She manages by being a perfectionist who is hyperorganized (all the hangers in her closet match). Her self-control is present in her personal as well as her professional life. She can walk into an antiques store, desire a choice piece of 18th-century English furniture, and then walk out, without buying, just to think it over.Correction: June 9, 1999, Wednesday  A Public Lives profile last Wednesday about Candace K. Beinecke, a partner with the Manhattan law firm of Hughes, Hubbard & Reed, referred imprecisely to the precedent set by her appointment to head the firm. Another sizable firm in New York, Patterson, Belknap, Webb & Tyler, was managed from 1990 to 1997 by a woman, Antonia Grumbach. Continue reading the main story






